ORIGIN#¶

The MNIST dataset was created by Yann LeCun, Corinna Cortes, and Christopher J.C. Burgess.

The test set has 10,000 photos, whereas the training set contains 60000. A picture's dimensions are 28 pixels wide by 28 pixels high. An image in grayscale (one channel for intensity) is indicated by the last dimension of 1.

The organized data is prepared for model training. It is possible to assess the model's performance on untested data thanks to the division of the sets into training and testing sets.

Precision (0.88): The accuracy of 88.28% is the percentage of successfully identified cases. A high accuracy suggests the overall efficacy of the model.

Accuracy (0.87): Precision gauges how accurate optimistic forecasts are. With an accuracy of 87%, the model reduces false positives, which is vital when accuracy is essential.

Recall (0.88): Recall, or sensitivity, measures the model's capacity to capture all positive cases. The high recall of 88% implies a low rate of false negatives, which is significant in applications that require all positives to be identified.

F1 Rating (0.88): The F1 score balances precision and recall, resulting in a harmonic mean. The model achieves a substantial trade-off between accuracy and recall, as seen by its F1 score of 88%.

from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam

def create_model(learning_rate=0.001, batch_size=128):
    model = Sequential([
        Dense(128, input_shape=(784,), activation='relu'),
        Dense(64, activation='relu'),
        Dense(10, activation='softmax')
    ])
    
    optimizer = Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate)
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    
    return model

In [ ]:
def plot_training_history(history):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'])
    plt.title('Model Accuracy')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Validation'], loc='upper left')

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.title('Model Loss')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Validation'], loc='upper left')
    plt.show()

def find_best_epoch(history):
    val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
    min_val_loss = min(val_loss)
    best_epoch = val_loss.index(min_val_loss) + 1
    return best_epoch

def evaluate_model(model, weights, X_test, y_test):
    model.set_weights(weights)
    y_pred_prob = model.predict(X_test)
    y_pred = np.argmax(y_pred_prob, axis=1)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted')
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted')
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted')
    return accuracy, precision, recall, f1

# Evaluate and print metrics 
for i, (model, weights) in enumerate(zip([model1, model2, model3], [best_weights1, best_weights2, best_weights3]), start=1):
    accuracy, precision, recall, f1 = evaluate_model(model, weights, X_test_flat, y_test)
    print(f"Model {i} - Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}, Precision: {precision:.4f}, Recall: {recall:.4f}, F1 Score: {f1:.4f}")

def evaluate_model(model, X_test, y_test, class_names):
    y_pred_prob = model.predict(X_test)
    y_pred = np.argmax(y_pred_prob, axis=1)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted')
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted')
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted')
    incorrect_indices = [i for i in range(len(y_test)) if y_test[i] != y_pred[i]]
    return accuracy, precision, recall, f1, incorrect_indices

# Error analysis 
for i, (model, weights) in enumerate(zip([model1, model2, model3], [best_weights1, best_weights2, best_weights3]), start=1):
    accuracy, precision, recall, f1, incorrect_indices = evaluate_model(model, X_test_flat, y_test, class_names)
    print(f"Model {i} - Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}, Precision: {precision:.4f}, Recall: {recall:.4f}, F1 Score: {f1:.4f}")
    print(f"Incorrect Predictions for Model {i}: {len(incorrect_indices)}")
    
# image displaying
    num_samples = min(25, len(incorrect_indices))
    y_pred_prob = model.predict(X_test_flat)
    y_pred = np.argmax(y_pred_prob, axis=1)
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(5, 5, figsize=(15, 15))
    for j, index in enumerate(incorrect_indices[:num_samples]):
        row = j // 5
        col = j % 5
        axs[row, col].imshow(X_test_flat[index].reshape(28, 28), cmap='gray')
        axs[row, col].axis('off')
        axs[row, col].set_title(f"True: {class_names[y_test[index]]}\nPred: {class_names[y_pred[index]]}")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
